Bring a large #saucepan{} of @water{150%ml} to the boil with @salt{1/4%tsp} for the rice. Peel the @ginger{1} and then halve it. When boiling, add the @basmati rice{150%g} and the half piece of ginger. Cook for ~{12%minutes} then drain in a #sieve{}, pop back in the #pot{} and cover with a #lid{}.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #frying pan{} on medium high heat. Once hot, add the @diced chicken thigh{260%g}, season with @salt{} and @black pepper{} and fry until golden brown, ~{4-5%minutes}. Stir occasionally. While the chicken cooks, grate the remaining ginger, peel and grate the @garlic clove{2} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Once the chicken is brown, add the @tomato puree{30%g}, @garam masala{1}, grated ginger and half the garlic. Stir together, then pour in the @water{150%ml} and stir in the @chicken stock powder{1}. Bring to the boil and simmer until reduced by half.

While everything cooks, heat a drizzle of @oil{} in another frying pan on medium high heat. Once hot, add the @shredded Savoy cabbage{100%g} and a splash of @water{30%ml}. Season with @salt{} and @black pepper{}, then fry until nearly tender, ~{3-4%minutes}. Stir in the @mustard seeds{1} and remaining garlic and cook for ~{1%minute}. Remove from the heat and cover with a lid or #tin foil{}.

Once the sauce has reduced, stir in the @soured cream{150%g}. Bring just to the boil, then stir in the @unsalted butter{30%g} until melted. Remove from the heat. Taste and add salt and pepper if you feel it needs it.

Remove (and discard) the ginger from the rice and spoon the rice into #bowls{}. Top with the curry and serve the cabbage on the side. Enjoy!